A spokesman said: ‘In reality it gets its mechanics just slightly wrong. 

'You get a young bird and it comes to lay its first egg and it releases more than one egg yolk. It forms a shell around the egg and out pops a rather large egg with two egg yolks in it.’

The yolk is the tastiest and most nutritious part of the egg, because it contains high quality essential fats, vitamins and minerals, including B12, B6, A, K, E and folate.

It is also one of the few foods to naturally contain vitamin D, which is important for bones, particularly in children.

Yolks also contain most of the egg’s calcium, magnesium, potassium, sodium, selenium and iron.

The British free range double-yolkers, which are extra-large, are available from this weekend for £2.75 for a box of six, compared with a box of the store’s normal large free range eggs, which costs £2. 

